[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
     [1mssh-copy-id[0m is a script that uses ssh(1) to log into a remote machine[m
     (presumably using a login password, so password authentication should be[m
     enabled, unless you've done some clever use of multiple identities).  It[m
     assembles a list of one or more fingerprints (as described below) and[m
     tries to log in with each key, to see if any of them are already in‐[m
     stalled (of course, if you are not using ssh-agent(1) this may result in[m
     you being repeatedly prompted for pass-phrases).  It then assembles a[m
     list of those that failed to log in, and using ssh, enables logins with[m
     those keys on the remote server.  By default it adds the keys by append‐[m
     ing them to the remote user's [4m~/.ssh/authorized_keys[24m (creating the file,[m
     and directory, if necessary).  It is also capable of detecting if the re‐[m
     mote system is a NetScreen, and using its ‘set ssh pka-dsa key ...’ com‐[m
     mand instead.[m
[m
     The options are as follows:[m
[m
     [1m-i[0m [4midentity_file[24m[m
             Use only the key(s) contained in [4midentity_file[24m (rather than look‐[m
             ing for identities via ssh-add(1) or in the [1mdefault_ID_file[0m).  If[m
             the filename does not end in [4m.pub[24m this is added.  If the filename[m
             is omitted, the [1mdefault_ID_file[0m is used.[m
[m
             Note that this can be used to ensure that the keys copied have[m
             the comment one prefers and/or extra options applied, by ensuring[m
             that the key file has these set as preferred before the copy is[m
             attempted.[m
[m
     [1m-f[0m      Forced mode: doesn't check if the keys are present on the remote[m
             server.  This means that it does not need the private key.  Of[m
             course, this can result in more than one copy of the key being[m
             installed on the remote system.[m
[m
     [1m-n[0m      do a dry-run.  Instead of installing keys on the remote system[m
             simply prints the key(s) that would have been installed.[m
[m
     [1m-s[0m      SFTP mode: usually the public keys are installed by executing[m
             commands on the remote side.  With this option the user's[m
             [4m~/.ssh/authorized_keys[24m file will be downloaded, modified locally[m
             and uploaded with sftp.  This option is useful if the server has[m
             restrictions on commands which can be used on the remote side.[m
[m
