       The umask is used by [1mopen[22m(2), [1mmkdir[22m(2), and other system calls that create files to modify the permissions placed on newly created[m
       files or directories.  Specifically, permissions in the umask are turned off from the [4mmode[24m argument to [1mopen[22m(2) and [1mmkdir[22m(2).[m
[m
       Alternatively,  if  the  parent  directory has a default ACL (see [1macl[22m(5)), the umask is ignored, the default ACL is inherited, the[m
       permission bits are set based on the inherited ACL, and permission bits absent in the [4mmode[24m argument are turned off.  For  example,[m
       the following default ACL is equivalent to a umask of 022:[m
[m
           u::rwx,g::r-x,o::r-x[m
[m
       Combining  the  effect  of this default ACL with a [4mmode[24m argument of 0666 (rw-rw-rw-), the resulting file permissions would be 0644[m
       (rw-r--r--).[m
[m
       The constants that should be used to specify [4mmask[24m are described in [1minode[22m(7).[m
[m
       The typical default value for the process umask is [1mS_IWGRP [22m| [1mS_IWOTH [22m(octal 022).  In the usual case where the  [4mmode[24m  argument  to[m
       [1mopen[22m(2) is specified as:[m
[m
           [1mS_IRUSR [22m| [1mS_IWUSR [22m| [1mS_IRGRP [22m| [1mS_IWGRP [22m| [1mS_IROTH [22m| [1mS_IWOTH[0m[m
[m
       (octal 0666) when creating a new file, the permissions on the resulting file will be:[m
[m
           [1mS_IRUSR [22m| [1mS_IWUSR [22m| [1mS_IRGRP [22m| [1mS_IROTH[0m[m
[m
       (because 0666 & ~022 = 0644; i.e. rw-r--r--).[m
[m
[1mRETURN VALUE[0m[m
       This system call always succeeds and the previous value of the mask is returned.[m
[m
[1mSTANDARDS[0m[m
       POSIX.1-2008.[m
[m
[1mHISTORY[0m[m
       POSIX.1-2001, SVr4, 4.3BSD.[m
[m
[1mNOTES[0m[m
       A child process created via [1mfork[22m(2) inherits its parent's umask.  The umask is left unchanged by [1mexecve[22m(2).[m
[m
       It  is  impossible to use [1mumask[22m() to fetch a process's umask without at the same time changing it.  A second call to [1mumask[22m() would[m
       then be needed to restore the umask.  The nonatomicity of these two steps provides the potential for races in  multithreaded  pro‐[m
       grams.[m
[m
       Since  Linux  4.7,  the  umask  of  any  process  can be viewed via the [4mUmask[24m field of [4m/proc/[24mpid[4m/status[24m.  Inspecting this field in[m
       [4m/proc/self/status[24m allows a process to retrieve its umask without at the same time changing it.[m
[m
       The umask setting also affects the permissions assigned to POSIX IPC objects ([1mmq_open[22m(3), [1msem_open[22m(3),  [1mshm_open[22m(3)),  FIFOs  ([1mmk‐[0m[m
       [1mfifo[22m(3)),  and  UNIX  domain sockets ([1munix[22m(7)) created by the process.  The umask does not affect the permissions assigned to Sys‐[m
       tem V IPC objects created by the process (using [1mmsgget[22m(2), [1msemget[22m(2), [1mshmget[22m(2)).[m
[m
